Eh, posted my message to the wrong forum, so here is post for Value Investors:

I read through Graham's "Intelligent Investor" while in Galapagos, so now I
know :P that I should have at least 25% of portfolio in bonds at all times. :)
Unfortunately, I do not trust bond funds, even less than I trust stock funds.
IMHO, very tough for me to judge what the heck they hold and what the heck will
be the result. Graham is not very helpful with this either, since he recommends
either treasuries - the yield of which has been beaten down to nothing - or
your own diversification, which means at least 100K in bonds. At least he gives
pointers on how to choose the bonds, while if you buy a bond fund, you have no
clue what it has. And you cannot trust bond ratings at all at this time.

I must say that current situation is probably one of the FEW times in our lives
when a person SHOULD be 100% in stocks. The deals are just too good. So screw
the bonds. :) On the other hand, I'd like some education if someone wants to
talk on what bonds to buy.

I flipped GNW short term bonds for a wash, gained some on MS bond, gained some
on AIG bond. No losses so far. ;) All sold. I still hold DCE, IDG, BCS-C,
RBS-N. All of these are probably stinkers for Graham, but maybe OK for now for
me. Assuming I trust Euro government guarantees.

More about my impressions on Graham's book later.
